Senior year of college, I had a cover class with one of my favorite illustrators, @jonfosterstudios and he gave One Flew Over the Cuckoo’s Nest for an assignment. It was the first thing I did well on all semester, and all these years later I wanted to revisit the book/film to see what I’d do now. There’s much to look at in this one, narratively. I was homaging some of my favorite artists from that time in this like Jon, Sargent and Tiepolo. I used to go to the @risdmuseum often as an undergrad and study the Tiepolo fresco and Sargent paintings we had. If I wasn’t there I was studying painting books in the library or painting at home. Great memories from senior year.

It's simple. Take away all the art they are scraping the internet to sample from (I use that, since the similarities to music sampling are there) and they have nothing. The programs are built on our real artist's backs. Type in an artist's name and a subject matter and you get something as if it were painted by their hand has wide-ranging implications from stealing their careers to creating NSFW work as if they painted it or even take spaces in coveted comic convention artist alley spaces. Back in the day, if an artist had emulated another artist's style, they would be considered a clone hack, especially in illustration. I went through phases of emulating my influences, which I sought to shed and find my own voice. That's the point, you find you're own voice that makes you unique. Typing something into a program that spits out an image doesn't make you an artist and never ever will. Delusion is strong with so-called AI artists. The issue commercial artists have with AI is very specific with how it can potentially annihilate entire industries of creative makers by stealing their previous work through scraping and repackaging it. @photoshop has disappointed me with how they’ve implemented it into their software and apparently monetized it for “ai artists”, and people that use it should voice their concerns with their wallet and mouths against @adobe 
If you’re going to defend ai art to me, don’t. This topic (unlike others) has no gray area, and I don’t care for your defense of it. That’s all I’ll say on this. Follow @jonlamart, @kortizart for tons of great info on how this harms artists. #createDontScrape #conceptartassociation #artistsrights #aiart #antiai #art #conceptartist #design #ethicalai #legislation #regulation #unethical #illustration #illustrator #datalaundering #adobe #adobeai #adobephotoshop #photoshop

Trying out @turnercolourworks #titaniumwhite for the first time. I picked up a 250 ml at @jerrysartarama during their Black Friday sales and just now using it. I’m comparing 3 whites here: Titanium White, Mixing White, and White. Unsurprisingly, titanium white had the most opacity while mixing white was most transparent. I think I’ll be using more Titanium White going forward. I really liked it, especially when I need to layer paint. I did use the paint both transparently and opaquely here. Painting notes:
• when starting out with a simple line sketch, it’s always a good idea to look for general shapes first.
 
• if you can’t simplify what you’re looking at, you may get lost in details. Try blurring your vision by squinting or taking off glasses. This will reduce the info you are making the large shapes stand out.

• this happens due to the higher contrast shapes popping forward while lower contrast shapes recede.

• once your sketch is in place, I like to start in the high info areas like the eyes, since that area takes the most attention from the viewer and also to render.

• Thoughts on color mixing will be in another post with a longer edit of this. #illustrator

Zombie painting is one of my favorite pastimes. Some painters like landscapes or the figure and maybe even both. I like those too, but nothing is quite like painting the undead. 

The colors you can push can be garish, which is inherently a part of the decayed nature of zombies. Combining greens, blues, reds and purples give a striking contrasting color effect, which is an interesting way to explore color theory. 

I started this with a very loose sketch that I actually couldn’t see while painting. I knew this as I was drawing it, so I ended up pivoting to making the sketch consist of landmarks. The top of the head and bottom of the jaw along with the centerline indicating the eyes and nose location was all I needed. 

Since likeness wasn’t much of a factor I wasn’t too concerned with the drawing. 

The painting part started simply by establishing large areas like the bandanna, hair and working my way down. 

Then it’s a matter of refining shapes until the details are set.

The idea came quick but not without later adjustments, which you can see. I wanted the player to seem larger than life knowing I couldn’t use players or logos. Drawing the eagles out was my work around for the opponent. I was loosely inspired by NC Wyeth’s famed illustration of the cloud giant as many other illustrators have been over the decades. 

The only way I could think of adding the @tb12sports nod was to tag up the new lighthouse with banners.

I knew where I wanted the Game info text but not sure. At first, I had it on a banner held by an eagles mouth. I always thought this portrait of Tony Soprano’s Ma turned out well. The furrowed brow along with her intense stare with cold barely blue eyes always struck me as a way to connect that killer personality she had. When painting a chars portrait it’s always easier to be honest with the painting than when you’re painting an actual person. I doubt many would want to be portrayed like this, and if you do paint them as they are then you can potentially offend people. With fictional people it’s a lot easier to paint an honest portrayal of them. Well, that and they’re one dimensional to an extent. They live entirely within the fictional depiction, so the nuance while there is ultimately limited. Any thoughts on this? Nothing feels better than varnishing a painting after spending many hours creating. It marks the completion and brings finality. As much as it’s nice to make something, it’s also a great feeling to be done too. 

Sometimes the work takes a lot of time, and if you’re not stepping away from it then you risk overlooking issues within the work. Deadline oriented artwork can force you to miss this vital step, which within that context is understandable. However, in an ideal world the art isn’t done until the artist is satisfied. 

A selfish thought, but hey I’m an artist and it’s my birthday today! I’ll say what I want! Which one of you varnish your work? And digital artists can chime in here, of course. I would say don’t varnish an iPad or cintiq. That would just ruin your tech.

Can’t share what this is outside an obscure peak. I love going to cafes to draw. I started sketching in them while I was in college. I often went with my childhood best friend who was immensely talentless. What was so exciting was back then I was always learning something completely new with regards to craft. Whether purely technique driven or conceptual I was constantly discovering sometimes new. And it was mainly due to my excitement for learning with research. I often went to museums with my sketchbook to study master paintings trying to decode their language. Nowadays I still try to find my way to the cafes to work, but it’s solo and with an iPad. Today, I’m mostly concerned with discovering new things within my work, but it’s shifted from how it’s done to what could be done. I wonder how common my story is. I bet many of you have experienced something similar.

Back to what I mentioned in the reel… I get asked often here what brushes or settings or paint I use. A brush will not give you a professional look if there’s no skills underneath. There’s no shortcut to skill building. Practice may not make perfect, but it does help you improve on the things you practice. For me, I practiced every day for years on learning how to draw and later how to paint. I did life painting studies using objects I had, which were often coffee cups or paint tubes. I also greatly benefited from going to museums and seeing master artworks in person where I would get as close as I could to them, so I could study how they were done. I would take my sketchbook and take notes or draw directly from them. I also frequented the library taking out books on my favorite artists and painting books. This was all during my 20’s. I was smitten by art and I particular painting. If you find yourself lost on where to start, try going to a museum or a library! It will definitely be worth your while, and in the meantime get off the phone and make some real art! Happy arting!

Painting trees in #procreate for a poster illustration. This is for a musical in February. They wanted a painterly look, so I took inspiration from some of my first art heroes such as Sargent, Sorolla, Degas, Manet, Titian, Schmid, Rembrandt and others. 

Painting foliage like this can be daunting, so rather than painting individual leaves, I try to paint the impression of a cluster of single leaves. Also, I try to consider the distance the trees are seen and what I could actually see from that distance. I have great vision 20/20 still and had 20/15 for a long time (thanks to screens it’s gotten worse over time), but even with great depth perception I can’t see many details on faraway objects, so why paint them. The ability to zoom in with digital art makes this challenging. To combat against that I make sure to paint without zoom in and often paint the size I would feel most comfortable with if actually painting. This can be small of significantly larger than expected.
